WEBVTT

00:03.120 --> 00:04.620
April: 24 hours.

00:04.620 --> 00:07.880
1,440 minutes.

00:07.880 --> 00:10.960
86,400 seconds.

00:10.960 --> 00:13.080
That's all it takes
for a patient

00:13.080 --> 00:15.000
to go from sick to healthy,

00:15.000 --> 00:16.710
from hopeful to dire...

00:16.710 --> 00:17.790
[ Tapping ]

00:17.790 --> 00:19.040
Oh!

00:19.040 --> 00:20.380
Sun's up, Doc.
I'm outta here.

00:20.380 --> 00:21.920
Let you sleep
as long as I could.

00:21.920 --> 00:23.540
[ Phone chimes ]

00:23.540 --> 00:26.290
♪♪

00:26.290 --> 00:27.540
Oh, so ridic.

00:27.540 --> 00:32.920
♪♪

00:35.710 --> 00:38.330
Teddy: Ja, ja, ich komme --
I'm coming.

00:38.330 --> 00:41.250
♪♪

00:41.250 --> 00:44.000
Okay, okay, okay,
keep your pants on --

00:44.000 --> 00:47.250
♪ I want you closer to me ♪

00:47.250 --> 00:49.540
They're on.

00:49.540 --> 00:51.330
Oh, my God!

00:51.330 --> 00:52.790
Hi!

00:52.790 --> 00:55.210
Owen: One day can bring you back
from the brink --

00:55.210 --> 00:57.250
change your entire life
with one heartbeat,

00:57.250 --> 00:59.540
one single breath.

00:59.540 --> 01:01.620
What the hell
are you doing here?

01:01.620 --> 01:03.710
♪ Say my name ♪

01:03.710 --> 01:06.170
Meredith: It's why doctors
watch you like a hawk,

01:06.170 --> 01:07.420
hold you for observation.

01:07.420 --> 01:09.460
Hey, grab this for me?
I'll be right there.

01:09.460 --> 01:11.880
Hey, you break it,
you buy it.

01:11.880 --> 01:13.830
[ Chuckles ]

01:13.830 --> 01:18.250
It's why we behave as if
your every move, every sound...

01:18.250 --> 01:20.420
Can I help you,
doctor...

01:20.420 --> 01:22.330
Uh, Dr. Marsh.
No, I'm fine, I'm good.

01:22.330 --> 01:24.500
I'm great. [ Sighs ]

01:24.500 --> 01:26.750
Just, um --
I had a kidney transplant.

01:26.750 --> 01:28.000
...every input...

01:28.000 --> 01:29.540
I can see that.
Congratulations.

01:29.540 --> 01:31.830
I can also see your ride
is leaving without you.

01:31.830 --> 01:33.420
...and output.

01:33.420 --> 01:35.170
No, when I said I had
a kidney transplant,

01:35.170 --> 01:36.790
I meant I had
a...kidney transplant.

01:36.790 --> 01:39.000
Just a little one.
I'm five-weeks post-op,

01:39.000 --> 01:40.460
and I'm -- I'm great.
I'm just...

01:40.460 --> 01:41.710
...is life or death.

01:41.710 --> 01:43.710
Dr. Marsh!
Can I get a gurney over here?!

01:43.710 --> 01:45.170
Man: I got it!

01:45.170 --> 01:48.420
Because it is.

01:55.380 --> 01:58.830
Okay, I'm not finding you
in the system, Mr. Zigler.

01:58.830 --> 02:01.500
Possibly because my last name
is Rigler, with an R.

02:01.500 --> 02:03.330
Ah. I'm sorry.

02:03.330 --> 02:06.120
It happens to the best of us,
Dr. Zepner?

02:06.120 --> 02:09.380
Ah, here you are.
Okay.

02:09.380 --> 02:11.620
You were here a week ago
with diverticulitis.

02:11.620 --> 02:13.000
-Yeah.
-You saw Dr. Bailey.

02:13.000 --> 02:14.670
Yeah, it's the third time
it happened to me,

02:14.670 --> 02:16.250
and she gave me antibiotics --
each time.

02:16.250 --> 02:18.420
She didn't suggest
surgery?

02:18.420 --> 02:20.500
Well, she said
that antibiotics would be

02:20.500 --> 02:22.880
the less-invasive option,
and I really wanted to go

02:22.880 --> 02:24.250
on my synagogue's
youth trip.

02:24.250 --> 02:25.830
You a little old for that?

02:25.830 --> 02:28.500
[ Chuckles ] I'm a rabbi,
and I've been around long enough

02:28.500 --> 02:30.540
to know you don't stick
a junior rabbi

02:30.540 --> 02:32.710
with a bunch of hormonal teens
on a weekend trip.

02:32.710 --> 02:34.620
[ Chuckles ]

02:34.620 --> 02:37.210
Anyway, I started feeling like I
was coming down with something,

02:37.210 --> 02:39.750
and...
and then I got this rash.

02:39.750 --> 02:41.790
Which I thought it would get
better in a few days,

02:41.790 --> 02:46.170
but it got worse --
a lot -- a lot worse.

02:46.170 --> 02:47.500
-Can I take a look?
-Yeah.

02:50.120 --> 02:51.920
Here we go.

02:53.750 --> 02:54.750
Yeah.

02:54.750 --> 02:56.120
Okay.

02:58.290 --> 03:00.290
O...kay.
-Yeah.

03:00.290 --> 03:02.250
All right.

03:02.250 --> 03:05.120
Page Dr. Avery, and tell
the burn unit we're on our way.

03:05.120 --> 03:07.080
[ Groans ]

03:07.080 --> 03:10.540
♪♪

03:10.540 --> 03:12.080
Teddy: So, tell me.

03:12.080 --> 03:13.580
Tell you what?

03:13.580 --> 03:15.120
Whatever it is
that you wanted to say,

03:15.120 --> 03:17.000
but you couldn't say
in an e-mail or over the phone,

03:17.000 --> 03:19.000
that you had to show up at my
door in the middle of the night.

03:19.000 --> 03:20.620
I mean, it must be --

03:20.620 --> 03:21.960
Is it Amelia's tumor?

03:21.960 --> 03:23.460
No, no,
it's nothing like that.

03:23.460 --> 03:25.460
Oh, I...
Is she pregnant?

03:25.460 --> 03:27.040
Owen, are you
going back to Iraq?

03:27.040 --> 03:28.250
Will you just tell me
what it is?

03:28.250 --> 03:29.250
I can't take it.

03:29.250 --> 03:31.210
Amelia and I are done.

03:33.250 --> 03:35.380
We're done, Teddy.

03:37.420 --> 03:41.210
So, for the first time,
you and me...

03:41.210 --> 03:44.040
there's nothing
standing in our way.

03:49.250 --> 03:51.210
Okay. So,
I said something,

03:51.210 --> 03:54.080
so you gotta
say something, so...

03:57.500 --> 04:02.080
♪♪

04:02.080 --> 04:06.620
♪♪

04:06.620 --> 04:11.380
♪♪

04:11.380 --> 04:16.710
♪♪

04:16.710 --> 04:18.830
Go ahead -- ask.

04:18.830 --> 04:21.250
I wasn't going to.

04:21.250 --> 04:23.380
You want to know
why I was operating

04:23.380 --> 04:25.790
not six weeks
post-kidney-transplant.

04:25.790 --> 04:29.210
You're dying to know, but you're
too polite to ask, so ask.

04:29.210 --> 04:31.830
I'm not polite.
It's none of my business.

04:31.830 --> 04:33.080
Mm-hmm.

04:33.080 --> 04:34.290
The thought did cross my mind.

04:34.290 --> 04:36.250
[ Both laugh ]

04:36.250 --> 04:37.500
Well, you know
what they say --

04:37.500 --> 04:38.830
doctors make
the worst patients.

04:40.500 --> 04:42.210
I'm rejecting it,
aren't I?

04:42.210 --> 04:43.540
That's what's happening --

04:43.540 --> 04:45.420
I'm rejecting my kidney,
or I formed a clot.

04:45.420 --> 04:46.960
Have you had
any other symptoms --

04:46.960 --> 04:48.290
oliguria, nausea, vomiting?

04:48.290 --> 04:50.170
Nothing. Up until
a few hours ago, I was fine.

04:50.170 --> 04:52.330
A few hours ago, you were
supposed to be on medical leave.

04:52.330 --> 04:54.330
[ Laughs ] I was, but my pain's
been at a consistent 3,

04:54.330 --> 04:56.920
and I've been off
narcotics for weeks.

04:56.920 --> 04:58.250
What's your
immunosuppressive regimen?

04:58.250 --> 04:59.460
Tacro, azathioprine,

04:59.460 --> 05:01.790
and I stopped prednisone
post-op day 4.

05:01.790 --> 05:03.210
Any mTOR inhibitors?

05:03.210 --> 05:05.670
No. I'm keeping that bullet
in the chamber.

05:05.670 --> 05:07.710
For the next time
you defy doctors' orders

05:07.710 --> 05:10.290
and perform an organ recovery
that someone else could've done?

05:10.290 --> 05:12.080
I mean, come on.
You cannot expect surgeons

05:12.080 --> 05:14.620
to just sit on the sidelines
watching surgeries go by.

05:14.620 --> 05:16.540
It's not gonna happen.

05:16.540 --> 05:20.290
I donated half of my liver.
I spent the month in a bed.

05:20.290 --> 05:22.290
Yeah, and I bet you hated
every second of it.

05:22.290 --> 05:24.120
[ Chuckles ]

05:27.170 --> 05:29.120
Vicki Greenberg.

05:29.120 --> 05:33.170
59 years old, fantastic mom,
even better grandmother.

05:33.170 --> 05:35.000
She can decoupage
like a rock star

05:35.000 --> 05:36.710
and makes
a ridiculously good salmon.

05:36.710 --> 05:38.120
Your favorite patient.

05:38.120 --> 05:39.790
Six years she's been
waiting for that liver.

05:39.790 --> 05:42.330
Me? I was on dialysis for
a month when I got my kidney.

05:42.330 --> 05:44.290
A month is hell,
but it's nothing.

05:44.290 --> 05:46.670
For six years, Vicki's been
miserable, dying.

05:46.670 --> 05:49.120
You think I was gonna leave that
in anyone else's hands but mine?

05:49.120 --> 05:50.830
-No.
-No.

05:50.830 --> 05:53.960
So I came back a week early, and
I was fine until I wasn't.

05:53.960 --> 05:57.040
Just...tell me I didn't screw
this up, Dr. Grey.

05:57.040 --> 05:58.580
Tell me I'm not gonna
lose this kidney.

05:58.580 --> 06:00.790
Well, we have to wait
for your labs to come back.

06:00.790 --> 06:03.710
I'll do an ultrasound, and let's
just not get ahead of ourselves.

06:03.710 --> 06:05.380
[ Chuckles ]

06:05.380 --> 06:06.960
Too late.

06:06.960 --> 06:08.170
[ Phone rings ]

06:08.170 --> 06:10.960
[ Indistinct talking ]

06:10.960 --> 06:13.170
Oh. Hey.
What's the good word, Doc?

06:16.120 --> 06:19.170
I'm not making
my synagogue trip, am I?

06:19.170 --> 06:21.420
Which means someone's
gonna get pregnant, or drunk --

06:21.420 --> 06:22.830
probably both.

06:22.830 --> 06:23.830
April: Rabbi --

06:23.830 --> 06:25.580
Oh, no, please -- Eli.

06:25.580 --> 06:28.170
I mean, you're shellacking
half my body in Vaseline.

06:28.170 --> 06:30.170
I think we can dispense
with the formalities.

06:30.170 --> 06:32.170
[ Sighs ]

06:32.170 --> 06:34.790
Eli, you have
toxic epidermal necrolysis,

06:34.790 --> 06:36.620
also known as TEN.

06:36.620 --> 06:39.250
It's a reaction to the
antibiotics you were prescribed.

06:39.250 --> 06:42.120
It's what's causing your skin
to separate from itself.

06:42.120 --> 06:45.620
That sounds...about as
disgusting as it looks.

06:45.620 --> 06:46.960
[ Sighs ]

06:46.960 --> 06:50.380
I-I thought I took the
antibiotics as prescribed.

06:50.380 --> 06:53.920
You did. TEN is something that
just happens to some patients.

06:53.920 --> 06:55.750
Nobody's really sure why.

06:55.750 --> 06:58.420
Hard to believe
that something this disgusting

06:58.420 --> 07:00.620
just...happens.

07:00.620 --> 07:02.420
Dr. Kepner and I are gonna do
our very best

07:02.420 --> 07:03.830
to keep you comfortable

07:03.830 --> 07:06.460
and prevent this thing
from progressing any further.

07:06.460 --> 07:08.830
Oh, good.
'Cause I gotta be honest --

07:08.830 --> 07:10.750
this is not my best look.

07:10.750 --> 07:12.960
[ Groans ]

07:12.960 --> 07:14.880
You sure there's
no one we can call?

07:14.880 --> 07:16.080
A family member --

07:16.080 --> 07:19.120
Oh, my wife, Elyse.
She's on a train.

07:19.120 --> 07:21.460
She's on her way back
from visiting her mother.

07:21.460 --> 07:23.750
I don't really...
want to worry her.

07:23.750 --> 07:25.830
Eli...

07:27.250 --> 07:29.380
You're saying worry her.

07:29.380 --> 07:31.540
Couldn't hurt to have
her company is all.

07:36.710 --> 07:38.500
[ Indistinct announcement
on P.A. ]

07:38.500 --> 07:40.250
[ Sighs ]

07:40.250 --> 07:42.670
[ Door closes ]

07:42.670 --> 07:44.580
How is he?

07:44.580 --> 07:47.960
You know the expression
"makes his flesh crawl"?

07:47.960 --> 07:49.290
Yeah, he's kind of
like that,

07:49.290 --> 07:51.210
except in a hundred times
more pain.

07:51.210 --> 07:53.920
Oh.
He had diverticulitis.

07:53.920 --> 07:55.420
I gave him antibiotics --

07:55.420 --> 07:57.500
For the third time.
You didn't want to --

07:57.500 --> 07:59.500
I don't know --
try something different?

07:59.500 --> 08:02.790
I made a judgment call
based on the standard of care.

08:02.790 --> 08:05.330
You can take antibiotics
a dozen times and no reaction.

08:05.330 --> 08:07.210
It's random.
It's awful, but it's random.

08:07.210 --> 08:08.960
You didn't
do anything wrong.

08:08.960 --> 08:11.500
Look, I-I can
take over from here.

08:11.500 --> 08:13.710
He was my patient.
-No, no. No way.

08:13.710 --> 08:16.290
No, I'm not gonna let
you go in there and
tell him you screwed up

08:16.290 --> 08:18.330
and then sit by his bedside
and make it all about you.

08:18.330 --> 08:20.080
April.
April, you know
that's not fair.

08:20.080 --> 08:22.120
All right? Any one of us
could've done the same thing.

08:22.120 --> 08:23.790
Yeah, but we didn't,
and she did,

08:23.790 --> 08:25.380
and I'm not about
to let her sit vigil

08:25.380 --> 08:26.580
while
he circles the drain.

08:26.580 --> 08:28.170
I know you're going
through something.

08:28.170 --> 08:29.250
I want to help.
I truly do.

08:29.250 --> 08:30.420
But that doesn't mean
you --

08:30.420 --> 08:32.170
This has nothing
to do with me, Jackson.

08:32.170 --> 08:33.580
I am just trying
to clean up her mess.

08:33.580 --> 08:36.460
We've all seen his labs.
He has a SCORTEN of 5.

08:36.460 --> 08:38.250
We can give him
as much care as we want,

08:38.250 --> 08:40.330
but he'll be lucky if
he makes it through the night.

08:40.330 --> 08:42.380
And if he doesn't,
that's on her.

08:42.380 --> 08:44.290
Fair or not.

08:44.290 --> 08:48.620
♪♪

08:48.620 --> 08:53.290
♪♪

09:00.960 --> 09:02.620
No thrombosis in the renal
artery. That's good.

09:02.620 --> 09:04.120
No hydronephrosis.

09:04.120 --> 09:06.420
No fluid collections,
no obstructions,

09:06.420 --> 09:09.000
cysts, abscesses...

09:09.000 --> 09:10.040
Yeah.

09:10.040 --> 09:11.460
Looks good.

09:11.460 --> 09:13.670
One hurdle down,
one more to go.

09:13.670 --> 09:17.000
Oh, and Mayo called and said
that Vicki's transplant surgery

09:17.000 --> 09:18.620
is going off
without a hitch.

09:18.620 --> 09:21.500
She's gonna give me so much crap
for bailing on her surgery.

09:21.500 --> 09:24.290
Well, she'll live --
quite literally.

09:24.290 --> 09:26.960
So when do I get
my labs back?

09:26.960 --> 09:28.380
[ Bed motor whirring ]

09:28.380 --> 09:29.210
Soon.

09:31.000 --> 09:33.380
Well, you don't suppose
slipping a cool $20

09:33.380 --> 09:35.540
to the boys down at the lab
would help speed this up,

09:35.540 --> 09:36.830
do you?
-I'm afraid not.

09:36.830 --> 09:38.040
How 'bout a $50?

09:38.040 --> 09:40.080
[ Chuckles ]
How's your pain?

09:40.080 --> 09:41.380
Me? I'm all good.

09:41.380 --> 09:43.000
Perfect, painless,
Marathon ready,

09:43.000 --> 09:44.420
or at least a strong 10K.

09:44.420 --> 09:45.750
Mm-hmm.
How'd it work out for you

09:45.750 --> 09:47.040
last time you pretended
you were fine?

09:47.040 --> 09:48.830
That's, uh --
That's a good point.

09:48.830 --> 09:51.170
I'd say
I'm about a 3, 3 1/2,

09:51.170 --> 09:52.580
but I'm gonna
muscle through.

09:52.580 --> 09:54.210
Is this you playing
it tough?

09:54.210 --> 09:56.500
Because you just did
a liver recovery

09:56.500 --> 09:58.460
5 weeks post-op
from your own surgery.

09:58.460 --> 09:59.790
No, no, no, no.

09:59.790 --> 10:02.330
This is me trying to avoid
an unnecessary addiction

10:02.330 --> 10:03.670
to opioids,
if I can help it.

10:03.670 --> 10:05.120
Slippery slope and all.

10:05.120 --> 10:07.880
Great. As soon as those labs
come in, I'm gonna let you know.

10:07.880 --> 10:10.540
This is the part where you
leave me, sad and alone,

10:10.540 --> 10:12.540
leaving me no choice
but to contemplate

10:12.540 --> 10:16.330
my dark, miserable, kidney-less
future, so sad and so alone?

10:16.330 --> 10:18.670
You're the one who said you
didn't want to call any family.

10:18.670 --> 10:21.460
That is true. That's because
Charlotte is a 16-year-old

10:21.460 --> 10:23.620
who'll fail calculus
if she misses her mid-term,

10:23.620 --> 10:25.790
and I am way too math-dumb to
pull her out of that hole.

10:27.790 --> 10:29.500
And yet you're
a transplant surgeon.

10:29.500 --> 10:31.170
Oh, yeah.
World class.

10:31.170 --> 10:33.040
You felt the need
to add that?

10:33.040 --> 10:36.380
When I'm talking to
Harper Avery-winning
Meredith Grey, yeah, I do.

10:36.380 --> 10:38.460
See? You don't even need
any visitors.

10:38.460 --> 10:40.790
You have so much Internet
stalking to do.
[ Chuckles ]

10:40.790 --> 10:42.750
I really do need
to go check on my patients.

10:42.750 --> 10:44.540
W-Well, uh,
tell me about them.

10:44.540 --> 10:47.290
Traditional stuff or another
abdominal-wall transplant?

10:47.290 --> 10:49.580
I am doing
two lap choles

10:49.580 --> 10:52.580
and repairing
a transected biliary duct.

10:52.580 --> 10:54.330
Mm.
How thin is the duct?

10:54.330 --> 10:55.880
2 millimeters.

10:55.880 --> 10:56.830
-Damn.
-Right?

10:56.830 --> 10:59.000
[ Both laugh ]

11:00.960 --> 11:03.380
So, is, uh -- is Charlotte
your daughter, or...?

11:03.380 --> 11:06.210
Uh, my niece.
Uh, Erica, my sister,

11:06.210 --> 11:09.330
she's a --
she's a limited person.

11:09.330 --> 11:11.960
She's got a gig heart
and good intentions,

11:11.960 --> 11:13.460
just zero follow-through.

11:13.460 --> 11:14.710
Well,
that's polite of you.

11:14.710 --> 11:15.540
Oh, you want the truth?

11:15.540 --> 11:16.710
Always.

11:16.710 --> 11:18.330
Uh...

11:18.330 --> 11:21.210
My selfish little sister
did one thing right

11:21.210 --> 11:22.880
in her selfish little life,

11:22.880 --> 11:24.580
and then she crapped
all over that,

11:24.580 --> 11:26.290
so I stepped up.

11:26.290 --> 11:28.330
I took Charlotte in,
and...

11:28.330 --> 11:30.540
it's the best thing
I ever did.

11:30.540 --> 11:33.880
What about you? You got kids,
nieces, pets, stowaways?

11:33.880 --> 11:35.330
What are we
talking about here?

11:35.330 --> 11:36.330
I do.
I have three kids.

11:36.330 --> 11:37.580
Wow.

11:37.580 --> 11:38.960
And an occasional
stowaway.

11:38.960 --> 11:40.210
-I...
-What's the matter?

11:40.210 --> 11:42.250
I'm just looking for your
superhero cape is all.

11:42.250 --> 11:44.000
-I'm not seeing it.
-I have a lot of help.

11:44.000 --> 11:45.170
Oh, do you?
What's that like?

11:45.170 --> 11:47.170
Your kids have a dad?

11:47.170 --> 11:49.210
They did.

11:52.040 --> 11:53.960
All right,
million-dollar question --

11:53.960 --> 11:55.710
what would you do
if you weren't a doctor?

11:55.710 --> 11:57.540
I --

11:57.540 --> 11:59.290
There is nothing
I would rather be.

11:59.290 --> 12:01.000
No, I mean, what if
you couldn't be a doctor?

12:01.000 --> 12:02.210
What then?
What's your Plan B?

12:02.210 --> 12:03.380
There's no Plan B.

12:03.380 --> 12:05.710
There really
hasn't ever been a Plan B.

12:05.710 --> 12:08.000
So, wait, wait. You had visions
of cutting people's bowels open

12:08.000 --> 12:09.040
straight out of the womb,

12:09.040 --> 12:10.380
and it's been
smooth sailing ever since?

12:10.380 --> 12:12.080
Really?
-Yes. Well, there was, like,

12:12.080 --> 12:14.040
a switch from neuro to general,
but pretty much, yeah.

12:14.040 --> 12:16.580
Wow. That is...

12:16.580 --> 12:17.960
Crazy.

12:17.960 --> 12:20.460
Well, I was gonna say amazing,
but, yeah, "crazy" will do.

12:20.460 --> 12:22.670
So, what about you?
You just woke up one morning

12:22.670 --> 12:24.580
and couldn't decide whether you
wanted to make French toast

12:24.580 --> 12:25.880
or become
a transplant surgeon?

12:25.880 --> 12:28.540
I wasn't exactly a legacy,
if that's what you mean.

12:28.540 --> 12:30.540
First one in my family to go
to college, actually.

12:30.540 --> 12:32.960
And you work at one of the best
hospitals in the world.

12:32.960 --> 12:34.710
Your mother must be
so disappointed.

12:34.710 --> 12:37.580
Well, I'd like to think she'd
be a little proud, yeah.

12:37.580 --> 12:39.290
♪♪

12:39.290 --> 12:40.540
When did she pass?

12:40.540 --> 12:41.580
I was 15.

12:41.580 --> 12:43.380
Oh.

12:43.380 --> 12:45.710
Tough age.
-Yeah, she was -- she was kind.

12:45.710 --> 12:47.540
And strange.

12:47.540 --> 12:49.210
And a terrible dresser.

12:49.210 --> 12:52.170
Impossibly smart.

12:52.170 --> 12:53.880
She had heart failure.

12:53.880 --> 12:55.670
She was on a list
a long time.

12:55.670 --> 12:57.000
♪♪

12:57.000 --> 12:59.170
Hearts
are hard to come by.

12:59.170 --> 13:01.710
Kidneys aren't as easy
as you'd think, either.

13:01.710 --> 13:03.540
No, they're not.

13:03.540 --> 13:06.120
So she's why you decided to
became a transplant surgeon?

13:06.120 --> 13:07.540
No, I-I loved cardio,
I loved neuro,

13:07.540 --> 13:08.750
I loved all of it,
really.

13:08.750 --> 13:11.620
I just -- I just
couldn't sit still.

13:11.620 --> 13:14.290
Transplant surgeons, you're
always in another city --

13:14.290 --> 13:15.830
in another country,
if you're lucky.

13:15.830 --> 13:17.540
Plus, I like to fly.

13:17.540 --> 13:18.540
Mnh.

13:18.540 --> 13:19.540
What? Not a fan?

13:19.540 --> 13:22.540
-No.
-[ Laughs ]

13:22.540 --> 13:24.460
♪♪

13:24.460 --> 13:25.540
So, where do you keep it?

13:25.540 --> 13:26.710
Keep what?

13:26.710 --> 13:28.080
Your Harper Avery.

13:28.080 --> 13:30.460
[ Laughs ]
Okay, I just -- I really --

13:30.460 --> 13:32.120
Nick, I have patients.

13:32.120 --> 13:34.920
Is it dead center on the mantel?
Fancy glass case in the study?

13:34.920 --> 13:36.960
What, did you just chuck it
in some closet somewhere?

13:36.960 --> 13:39.080
Tell me, tell me, tell me.
What, is it a hat rack?

13:39.080 --> 13:41.330
As soon
as your labs come in,

13:41.330 --> 13:43.580
I will come down
and let you know.

13:43.580 --> 13:44.880
-Okay.
-Okay?

13:44.880 --> 13:47.250
Just one last question.

13:48.620 --> 13:50.670
Just answer me this,
Dr. Grey --

13:50.670 --> 13:51.710
Meredith.

13:51.710 --> 13:53.540
Meredith.

13:53.540 --> 13:56.290
Do you think I'm gonna
lose this kidney?

13:56.290 --> 13:58.170
Your ultrasound
looked great,

13:58.170 --> 14:00.080
but until your other labs
come back,

14:00.080 --> 14:01.960
there's no way
to definitively know --

14:01.960 --> 14:04.210
Yeah. Well,
I'm asking what you think.

14:04.210 --> 14:06.540
I don't know.

14:06.540 --> 14:10.500
♪♪

14:17.290 --> 14:20.080
Teddy: [ Laughing ]

14:20.080 --> 14:21.540
Owen:
Are you good there?

14:21.540 --> 14:24.080
[ Laughing continues ]

14:24.080 --> 14:28.120
You know, it's possible
I imagined this moment once --

14:28.120 --> 14:31.120
okay, a hundred times -- but it
didn't ever involve laughing.

14:31.120 --> 14:33.790
You're in my bed,
in Germany.

14:33.790 --> 14:36.170
I mean, you are in my bed,
in Germany.

14:36.170 --> 14:38.420
Owen Hunt,
naked, in my bed.

14:38.420 --> 14:40.080
Yeah, yeah.
I don't even like Germany.

14:40.080 --> 14:41.580
Yeah, me neither!

14:41.580 --> 14:43.290
[ Both laugh ]

14:51.460 --> 14:53.960
I know I should ask you why
you're here, but...

14:53.960 --> 14:55.830
-I told you.
-It's just...

14:55.830 --> 14:58.540
You imagined this, too?

14:58.540 --> 15:01.290
I imagined this, too.

15:03.210 --> 15:09.210
♪♪

15:09.210 --> 15:16.000
♪♪

15:16.000 --> 15:17.710
No, absolutely not.

15:17.710 --> 15:19.170
When are you gonna admit
that you're wrong?

15:19.170 --> 15:20.170
It was a CABG.

15:20.170 --> 15:21.540
It was a coronary artery
dissection.

15:21.540 --> 15:23.670
CABG.
It was a freakin' CABG.

15:23.670 --> 15:26.120
I said that I would take the
coronary artery dissection.

15:26.120 --> 15:27.170
What was that guy?

15:27.170 --> 15:28.790
He was that annoying guy
with the --

15:28.790 --> 15:30.080
Ratliff, with the...

15:30.080 --> 15:31.710
Both: Tattoo of Jim Morrison
on his shoulder.

15:31.710 --> 15:33.620
Right, I was prepping him,
and then you walked in

15:33.620 --> 15:36.040
and started barking
like some crazed sea lion,

15:36.040 --> 15:38.080
and you told Sergeant Teller
to take the dissection,

15:38.080 --> 15:39.460
and I ended up
with the CABG.

15:39.460 --> 15:40.960
Oh, oh, oh!
And then, um...

15:40.960 --> 15:42.210
you made me assist
because you said

15:42.210 --> 15:43.290
that I put you
in the minors

15:43.290 --> 15:44.790
when you should've been
in the majors.

15:44.790 --> 15:47.460
Okay, I have never used a
baseball metaphor in my life.

15:47.460 --> 15:49.460
Ooh! You were pissed,
but you were excellent.

15:49.460 --> 15:51.000
I was.

15:51.000 --> 15:52.790
And you were
a sufficient assist.

15:52.790 --> 15:54.210
Sufficient.

15:54.210 --> 15:55.330
Yeah. What do
you want me to say?

15:55.330 --> 15:56.790
That you were flawless
and brilliant

15:56.790 --> 15:58.250
and you anticipated
my every move

15:58.250 --> 16:02.040
and I knew the moment that we
shared that O.R...

16:02.040 --> 16:04.540
that I wanted to do that
the rest of my life?

16:04.540 --> 16:06.290
I did.

16:06.290 --> 16:07.620
I mean,
with you assisting me,

16:07.620 --> 16:09.170
but, you know,
it's the same thing.

16:09.170 --> 16:11.670
[ Both laugh ]

16:11.670 --> 16:14.380
You are such a slob.

16:14.380 --> 16:16.710
[ Muffled ]
And you're beautiful.

16:16.710 --> 16:19.120
[ Laughing ] Oh, my God.

16:20.710 --> 16:23.460
This, right here,
when it snows, this is...

16:23.460 --> 16:26.830
this is the one time
I really love this place.

16:26.830 --> 16:28.040
Owen: [ Chuckles ]

16:28.040 --> 16:30.500
[ Sighs ]

16:30.500 --> 16:32.380
You remember when you made it
snow in the desert

16:32.380 --> 16:34.000
for our guys
in the 54th?

16:34.000 --> 16:35.540
[ Chuckles ]

16:35.540 --> 16:38.080
You blindfolded them,
and you put their face

16:38.080 --> 16:41.170
up to the machine so they could
feel it before it melted?

16:41.170 --> 16:42.830
It made them happy.

16:45.120 --> 16:46.500
You were so good
at that.

16:46.500 --> 16:48.120
All the grand gestures,

16:48.120 --> 16:50.540
you did it better
than anyone else I know.

16:57.290 --> 16:59.580
Owen, what are you
doing here?

16:59.580 --> 17:01.290
I told you.

17:01.290 --> 17:02.750
No, I mean...

17:02.750 --> 17:05.120
[ Sighs ]

17:05.120 --> 17:07.880
I mean, is -- is this it?

17:07.880 --> 17:09.620
Right here, this?
Is this --

17:09.620 --> 17:11.380
I mean -- [ Sighs ]

17:12.790 --> 17:14.920
Are you getting on a plane
tomorrow, and -- and -- and --

17:14.920 --> 17:17.000
and we have this...

17:17.000 --> 17:19.290
As amazing as this is,
this isn't --

17:19.290 --> 17:21.080
What?

17:21.080 --> 17:22.330
This isn't real.

17:22.330 --> 17:23.540
Why can't it be?

17:23.540 --> 17:26.170
Because I live a million miles
and time zones away,

17:26.170 --> 17:28.120
and I have a big life here,
Owen.

17:28.120 --> 17:30.120
Yeah, but you hate Germany,
so...

17:30.120 --> 17:31.920
Yeah, but I love my job,
and I love my friends.

17:31.920 --> 17:34.420
And there's this restaurant
on the corner, and they know me,

17:34.420 --> 17:36.710
and they make
this roast chicken --

17:36.710 --> 17:39.290
I mean, the best roasted chicken
that I've ever tasted before.

17:39.290 --> 17:41.120
And I'm opening up
a clinic for refugees,

17:41.120 --> 17:43.460
and I have the finances
and the resources,

17:43.460 --> 17:45.670
and it's finally,
finally happening.

17:45.670 --> 17:49.960
And I -- I have made a life here
for myself, and --

17:49.960 --> 17:51.620
And why
can't I be part of that?

17:54.000 --> 17:55.750
Do you want to be
a part of it?

17:55.750 --> 17:57.670
I mean, you would
move to Germany?

17:57.670 --> 17:59.420
Why not? I mean,
I'm a trauma surgeon.

17:59.420 --> 18:00.790
I could work with you --

18:00.790 --> 18:02.460
-For me.
-For you.

18:02.460 --> 18:05.380
Or -- Or I could find a job
at a different hospital,

18:05.380 --> 18:08.380
if that's not
what you want.

18:08.380 --> 18:13.540
I can move here
and be with you, and...

18:13.540 --> 18:16.000
And you'd be leaving Megan
behind and your mom.

18:18.580 --> 18:20.540
Or you could come back
to Seattle.

18:20.540 --> 18:22.540
Pierce is unreal,
and the two of you together --

18:22.540 --> 18:24.500
Or we could half and half
or go to Canada.

18:24.500 --> 18:25.580
[ Laughing ] Canada.

18:25.580 --> 18:27.290
Or I don't know.
I don't know.

18:27.290 --> 18:30.290
I haven't figured that
all out yet, but I just know --

18:30.290 --> 18:33.210
I just know
that I want to be with you.

18:33.210 --> 18:35.380
I just know
that I want you.

18:35.380 --> 18:38.670
This is not some grand gesture
or some -- some whimsical --

18:38.670 --> 18:40.290
Yeah.
Yeah, it is fast,

18:40.290 --> 18:42.420
and I haven't figured out
all the moves,

18:42.420 --> 18:45.210
but that doesn't make this
any less --

18:45.210 --> 18:49.580
I am in love
with you...Teddy.

18:49.580 --> 18:52.540
I realized I loved you
and how long I've loved you.

18:54.000 --> 18:55.830
So I got on a plane.

18:58.040 --> 18:59.750
You got on a plane.

18:59.750 --> 19:01.420
Yeah.

19:01.420 --> 19:03.210
I got on a plane.

19:03.210 --> 19:05.540
[ Laughs ]

19:22.670 --> 19:25.210
Owen: [ Sighs ]

19:25.210 --> 19:26.920
Stay a few days.

19:26.920 --> 19:30.080
I'll show you around
the hospital, and...

19:30.080 --> 19:32.500
we can go hiking
around Bismarck Tower.

19:32.500 --> 19:35.960
You can show me
your roasted chicken place.

19:35.960 --> 19:37.620
Yeah, back off.
That place is all mine.

19:37.620 --> 19:39.170
[ Both laugh ]

19:39.170 --> 19:41.880
So, can you? Stay?

19:41.880 --> 19:44.460
Sure. I'll make a couple calls.
Kepner can take my shifts.

19:44.460 --> 19:47.460
Sure. I mean,
just like that, sure.

19:47.460 --> 19:49.120
Teddy, I told you.

19:52.290 --> 19:54.670
Tell me
this doesn't scare you.

19:54.670 --> 19:56.210
Why should it?

19:56.210 --> 19:58.880
You know me.
I know you.

19:58.880 --> 20:00.580
This has been...

20:00.580 --> 20:02.210
[ Breathes deeply ]

20:03.880 --> 20:05.790
We know we work.

20:05.790 --> 20:07.500
What if it doesn't?

20:07.500 --> 20:08.540
Can't think like that.

20:08.540 --> 20:09.880
Yeah, but I do.
You know I do.

20:09.880 --> 20:11.830
You know
everything about me.

20:11.830 --> 20:14.460
You're my first call
in a crisis,

20:14.460 --> 20:18.670
or when I've just done the most
perfect LIMA to LAD anastomosis,

20:18.670 --> 20:22.290
and you just --
you make things real and better,

20:22.290 --> 20:25.790
and you tell me
when I'm being an ass.

20:25.790 --> 20:29.710
Yeah, I know.
You're my best friend, Owen.

20:29.710 --> 20:32.000
Isn't that
what they say?

20:32.000 --> 20:34.000
You should marry
your best friend?

20:34.000 --> 20:35.460
Oh, really?
So now we're getting married?

20:35.460 --> 20:36.790
No, I -- What I --

20:36.790 --> 20:38.040
You just got
out of a marriage.

20:38.040 --> 20:39.170
That led me to you.

20:39.170 --> 20:41.250
Teddy, I get
that you're scared,

20:41.250 --> 20:43.290
but there's no --
that's not a reason --

20:43.290 --> 20:46.790
Wait. What do you mean,
"led me to you"?

20:46.790 --> 20:49.540
Well, I just mean,
Amelia, she --

20:49.540 --> 20:51.290
Listen...

20:51.290 --> 20:53.000
marrying Amelia
was a mistake.

20:53.000 --> 20:54.830
You said it yourself.

20:54.830 --> 20:58.210
It was not a marriage, and she
and I, we can both admit that.

20:59.420 --> 21:01.460
She's --
Amelia's a gambler.

21:01.460 --> 21:02.710
Or she was a gambler.

21:02.710 --> 21:05.330
It's hard to tell the difference
between Tumor Amelia

21:05.330 --> 21:07.580
and Amelia Amelia,
but we took a gamble,

21:07.580 --> 21:09.620
and it fell apart because
it wasn't meant --

21:09.620 --> 21:13.670
My point is,
she was right.

21:13.670 --> 21:16.290
Being here with you, it makes
all the sense in the world.

21:16.290 --> 21:18.040
Wait. She said that?

21:18.040 --> 21:20.080
Well, not in so many --
She just...

21:22.290 --> 21:26.040
Listen, she knows me, and she
knows how much you mean to me,

21:26.040 --> 21:29.040
so when she said it, it --
it -- it just made sense.

21:29.040 --> 21:31.170
All I'm trying to say is,

21:31.170 --> 21:32.710
she is the one
who pointed out

21:32.710 --> 21:34.750
that there's always been
something between us,

21:34.750 --> 21:36.080
and she was right,
so I --

21:36.080 --> 21:37.710
[ Gasps ]

21:37.710 --> 21:39.620
So you got on a plane
to me.

21:39.620 --> 21:41.080
Yes.

21:41.080 --> 21:43.330
Teddy...

21:43.330 --> 21:45.080
Teddy, there's no reason
to make this --

21:45.080 --> 21:46.670
Wait.

21:46.670 --> 21:48.750
What were you -- What were you
doing when she said this?

21:48.750 --> 21:51.290
♪♪

21:51.290 --> 21:52.830
-Uh...
-Owen?

21:52.830 --> 21:54.380
[ Clears throat ]

21:54.380 --> 21:56.750
Owen.

21:56.750 --> 21:58.710
You were sleeping with her.

21:58.710 --> 22:00.330
Teddy...

22:00.330 --> 22:01.960
When?
When did she say this?

22:01.960 --> 22:06.710
♪♪

22:06.710 --> 22:08.040
Last night.

22:08.040 --> 22:10.210
[ Scoffs ]

22:10.210 --> 22:15.710
♪♪

22:23.330 --> 22:24.790
I was a near-impossible match,
you know.

22:24.790 --> 22:26.670
I took the one kidney in
my world someone could offer --

22:26.670 --> 22:28.420
my best friend.

22:28.420 --> 22:30.460
[ Breathes deeply ]

22:30.460 --> 22:33.120
If I have to look him in the eye
and tell him I blew it...

22:33.120 --> 22:34.830
But you can't think
like that.

22:34.830 --> 22:36.170
I can't help it.

22:36.170 --> 22:38.040
We won't know
until we know.

22:41.580 --> 22:45.330
I used to think shoe salesman --
for my Plan B.

22:45.330 --> 22:46.750
You have a thing
for feet?

22:46.750 --> 22:47.830
What, deal-breaker?

22:47.830 --> 22:49.250
I mean, kind of, yeah.

22:49.250 --> 22:51.250
There's no world
in which a shoe salesman

22:51.250 --> 22:53.380
comes home at night
and thinks about shoes.

22:53.380 --> 22:55.080
He goes to work,
he deals with feet

22:55.080 --> 22:57.250
and weird people all day,
but, hell, so do we.

22:57.250 --> 22:59.960
Except what's the worst thing
he can cause?

22:59.960 --> 23:01.960
Blisters?
Bad arch support?

23:01.960 --> 23:05.330
That job is the epitome
of "No Harm, No Foul."

23:05.330 --> 23:07.750
Plus,
actual vacation time.

23:07.750 --> 23:08.540
"Used to think."

23:08.540 --> 23:09.790
What's that?

23:09.790 --> 23:11.210
You said
you used to think

23:11.210 --> 23:13.000
that's what you would do
for a living.

23:13.000 --> 23:15.790
That's just what I consider when
a patient's lung craps out on me

23:15.790 --> 23:18.540
or the plane lands five minutes
too late to recover an organ.

23:18.540 --> 23:19.460
But that's not the fantasy.

23:19.460 --> 23:20.710
No.

23:20.710 --> 23:21.920
So what is?

23:21.920 --> 23:23.210
Your turn.

23:23.210 --> 23:25.620
My turn?
I'm just here to listen.

23:25.620 --> 23:26.670
No, you're not.

23:26.670 --> 23:27.670
I'm not?

23:27.670 --> 23:28.920
No.

23:28.920 --> 23:30.920
Okay.
Well, there was one time

23:30.920 --> 23:33.960
when I thought I would be
working at the multiplex

23:33.960 --> 23:37.000
with my best friend Cristina,
but that was just --

23:37.000 --> 23:38.380
Your version
of shoe salesman.

23:38.380 --> 23:40.420
More like hospital-mandated
therapy, but...

23:40.420 --> 23:42.210
Ooh! Now we're getting
to the good stuff.

23:42.210 --> 23:43.920
[ Laughs ]

23:43.920 --> 23:45.880
But you don't have
an answer, do you?

23:45.880 --> 23:48.170
You don't know what you would do
if you weren't a doctor.

23:50.330 --> 23:52.120
My dad took us
out to the Boundary Waters.

23:52.120 --> 23:53.620
You know them?
-No.

23:53.620 --> 23:56.000
Right on the edge,
between Minnesota and Canada.

23:56.000 --> 23:59.750
These huge stretches
of lake.

23:59.750 --> 24:02.750
You have to portage your canoes
on your shoulders for miles.

24:02.750 --> 24:06.290
Every morning, my dad would
take me out in a canoe.

24:06.290 --> 24:07.710
We'd be up so early,

24:07.710 --> 24:10.920
you could see the cobwebs
reflecting off the reeds.

24:10.920 --> 24:15.620
And just dead, eerie,
incredible silence.

24:15.620 --> 24:18.380
[ Breathes deeply ]

24:18.380 --> 24:21.420
My dad would get this look
on his face.

24:21.420 --> 24:24.210
If I couldn't be a doctor,
I'd go sit in that canoe

24:24.210 --> 24:25.830
until I felt --
even for a second --

24:25.830 --> 24:27.540
what he was feeling.

24:31.040 --> 24:32.460
Or you know what?
Screw it.

24:32.460 --> 24:34.290
I'll be a shoe salesman.
That's where it's at.

24:34.290 --> 24:35.500
Fewer mosquitoes, too.

24:35.500 --> 24:36.710
[ Laughs ]

24:36.710 --> 24:38.250
Hey, it's your turn.

24:38.250 --> 24:40.210
I just got way too personal
on our first date,

24:40.210 --> 24:41.790
so your turn.
-Excuse me?

24:41.790 --> 24:44.790
Joking.
That was me making a joke.

24:44.790 --> 24:46.170
I am your doctor.

24:46.170 --> 24:47.920
Hey, thank God
for that, right?

24:47.920 --> 24:50.500
Listen, the reality is, as soon
as I'm good to go here,

24:50.500 --> 24:52.460
I'm on a plane back
to Minnesota.

24:52.460 --> 24:54.790
Mayo's got my back.
You never have to see me again.

24:54.790 --> 24:57.330
Mm. Whew.

24:57.330 --> 25:00.540
So what's a little deep, dark
confession amongst friends?

25:02.460 --> 25:04.210
Okay.

25:04.210 --> 25:06.250
Um...

25:06.250 --> 25:07.750
Have you ever been
to Sardinia?

25:07.750 --> 25:09.460
-Sardinia.
-Mm.

25:09.460 --> 25:11.330
Nude beach
and a bottle of wine.

25:11.330 --> 25:12.920
Helluva party.
Excellent choice.

25:12.920 --> 25:14.880
So, when I was young,

25:14.880 --> 25:17.500
my girlfriend and I stayed
in this tiny village.

25:17.500 --> 25:21.540
And I think we paid
this woman like $2

25:21.540 --> 25:23.750
to crash at her house
and drink all of her wine.

25:23.750 --> 25:25.290
And she was 97.

25:25.290 --> 25:27.290
Her sister was 101.

25:27.290 --> 25:29.580
The neighbor was 99.

25:29.580 --> 25:32.750
And they grew their own food,
and they wandered

25:32.750 --> 25:36.420
these little cobblestone streets
with chickens to the beaches.

25:36.420 --> 25:38.460
Wait. I'm sorry. Did the
chickens wander on the beach,

25:38.460 --> 25:39.620
or how does that work?

25:39.620 --> 25:42.120
No, the people --
these incredible people --

25:42.120 --> 25:45.920
who were laughing and fighting
with the people they loved,

25:45.920 --> 25:47.710
and no one
was in any rush.

25:47.710 --> 25:49.120
No one had anywhere to go.

25:49.120 --> 25:50.380
And they were happy.

25:50.380 --> 25:52.250
So you want to go live
with the chickens

25:52.250 --> 25:53.330
and the happy people?

25:53.330 --> 25:54.670
-Yes.
-Okay.

25:54.670 --> 25:56.540
Me and my kids.

25:56.540 --> 25:59.210
And my sisters can come
because they can do the cooking

25:59.210 --> 26:01.120
and the growing
because, I mean, please.

26:01.120 --> 26:02.500
[ Chuckles ]

26:02.500 --> 26:04.210
And everyone's already
living

26:04.210 --> 26:06.290
till they were
a hundred years old, right?

26:06.290 --> 26:07.920
There's no cancer
or Alzheimer's,

26:07.920 --> 26:11.000
so there's no lives for me
to save, and...

26:11.000 --> 26:14.330
no one will die
on my watch.

26:14.330 --> 26:15.710
Sounds pretty good.

26:15.710 --> 26:18.000
Just me and my kids
and a hammock

26:18.000 --> 26:19.710
and a stack of books
that I'll buy

26:19.710 --> 26:21.670
with no intention
of ever reading.

26:21.670 --> 26:24.620
Mm. In this scenario, I don't
suppose there's any room

26:24.620 --> 26:26.920
on that hammock for someone
about your age?

26:26.920 --> 26:28.540
Brilliant
but not too brilliant,

26:28.540 --> 26:31.670
with one...debatably
functioning kidney?

26:31.670 --> 26:34.080
I mean, unless you wanna lug
a canoe over your head with me?

26:34.080 --> 26:36.000
'Cause
I'm game either way.

26:39.420 --> 26:40.670
[ Phone chimes ]

26:40.670 --> 26:42.580
Your labs.

26:42.580 --> 26:45.000
They're what?

26:45.000 --> 26:46.620
Dr. Grey?

26:46.620 --> 26:47.710
Damn it.

26:47.710 --> 26:48.920
Tell me.

26:48.920 --> 26:50.210
They're inconclusive.

26:50.210 --> 26:51.710
-Meredith...
-Um...okay.

26:51.710 --> 26:53.500
Wait.
-[ Breathes deeply ]

26:53.500 --> 26:55.380
The biopsy is normal.

26:55.380 --> 26:57.420
Your bloodwork is showing
a normal white count.

26:57.420 --> 26:58.580
What about my GFR?

26:58.580 --> 26:59.580
It's down.

26:59.580 --> 27:01.080
-Creatinine?
-It's doubled.

27:01.080 --> 27:02.580
But you also have
proteinuria.

27:02.580 --> 27:04.210
Something
isn't making sense.

27:04.210 --> 27:06.000
I can't lose my kidney,
Meredith, please.

27:08.580 --> 27:12.040
♪♪

27:12.040 --> 27:13.790
[ Ultrasound whooshes ]

27:13.790 --> 27:15.620
There it is. You have a clot
in your renal vein.

27:15.620 --> 27:18.290
[ Sighs ]

27:18.290 --> 27:20.790
We need to get him
up to the O.R. right now.

27:20.790 --> 27:23.380
Nothing showed up on
the ultrasound before. Why not?

27:23.380 --> 27:25.710
Because the flow to the vein
is so low, but it makes sense.

27:25.710 --> 27:28.040
You were on that plane.
You were standing in that O.R.

27:28.040 --> 27:29.710
Any one of these
could've caused a DVT

27:29.710 --> 27:31.500
to lodge itself
in your renal vein.

27:31.500 --> 27:33.540
Let's go, come on!
We gotta go, guys!

27:33.540 --> 27:35.210
♪♪

27:35.210 --> 27:36.330
-Meredith --
-Nick, listen,

27:36.330 --> 27:37.290
you need an embolectomy
right now

27:37.290 --> 27:38.460
if I'm gonna
save this kidney.

27:38.460 --> 27:39.750
Third drawer,
green cabinet.

27:39.750 --> 27:41.040
-Nick, I got this.
-No, no, no, no.

27:41.040 --> 27:42.330
Third drawer,
green cabinet.

27:42.330 --> 27:43.750
That's where the deed
to the house is

27:43.750 --> 27:45.540
and the passcodes for
Charlotte's college fund.

27:45.540 --> 27:46.750
She's got to go to college.

27:46.750 --> 27:48.460
I don't care for what,
but she's gotta go.

27:48.460 --> 27:50.040
She's kind and strong
and beautiful,

27:50.040 --> 27:51.250
and none of that will matter

27:51.250 --> 27:52.710
if she can't string together
a decent sentence.

27:52.710 --> 27:54.380
And tell her to stay the hell
away from drugs.

27:54.380 --> 27:55.500
Her mother never could,
and it ruined her.

27:55.500 --> 27:57.000
[ Bell dings ]
If she wants
to drink, drink,

27:57.000 --> 27:58.710
but there's an A.A. book
in her college folder, too,

27:58.710 --> 28:00.540
just in case.
Tell her, Meredith.

28:00.540 --> 28:02.080
Stay with me, Nick.

28:02.080 --> 28:03.580
Tell her for me, Meredith,
please.

28:03.580 --> 28:05.080
You'll tell her yourself.

28:05.080 --> 28:06.290
Let's go!

28:13.170 --> 28:14.330
Elyse.

28:14.330 --> 28:16.250
W-- Elyse?

28:16.250 --> 28:18.040
-Eli.
-Elyse?

28:18.040 --> 28:19.830
Your wife, Elyse,
is on her way.

28:19.830 --> 28:22.120
Just hang in there, Eli.
-Okay.

28:22.120 --> 28:25.000
I'm gonna turn up the bed warmer
to encourage wound healing.

28:25.000 --> 28:26.500
Huh? You're gonna
make it hotter?

28:26.500 --> 28:28.250
I'm sorry. Um...

28:28.250 --> 28:29.420
I can draw up
some morphine.

28:29.420 --> 28:31.580
No, no, no, no!
I don't want any pain meds.

28:31.580 --> 28:34.170
I don't want to be loopy.
[ Groans ]

28:34.170 --> 28:36.790
You couldn't
just pretend?

28:36.790 --> 28:38.330
I'm sorry?

28:38.330 --> 28:40.290
I think you're my wife
for two seconds.

28:40.290 --> 28:41.880
You couldn't just, you know,
roll with it?

28:41.880 --> 28:43.500
[ Both laugh ]

28:43.500 --> 28:44.880
[ Coughs ]

28:44.880 --> 28:46.920
Eli, I can tell you're in
a great deal of pain --

28:46.920 --> 28:49.250
You worry too much.
Anybody ever tell you that?

28:49.250 --> 28:51.420
Look, I'll sign
whatever papers you want.

28:51.420 --> 28:53.380
No morphine, no more tubes.
Just -- Okay?

28:53.380 --> 28:55.170
Until my wife, Elyse,
gets here, all right?

28:55.170 --> 28:56.710
-Okay, okay.
-Okay, good.

28:56.710 --> 28:58.620
Dr. Bailey's hovering.

28:58.620 --> 29:00.170
Unless
I'm imagining that, too.

29:00.170 --> 29:01.290
I'm sorry about that.

29:01.290 --> 29:02.580
She can come in
if she wants.

29:02.580 --> 29:03.710
She's fine where she is.

29:03.710 --> 29:04.750
You don't like her.

29:06.620 --> 29:08.290
She's my boss.

29:08.290 --> 29:09.670
She's a good one,
I can tell.

29:09.670 --> 29:11.040
She was a good doctor
to me, too.

29:13.380 --> 29:15.250
You don't think so?

29:15.250 --> 29:16.790
Well, she prescribed
the antibiotics,

29:16.790 --> 29:19.080
and now the antibiotics --
-Yeah, she was trying to save me

29:19.080 --> 29:20.500
from an unnecessary
surgery.

29:22.880 --> 29:24.830
She made a mistake.

29:24.830 --> 29:26.290
Is that
what you're saying?

29:26.290 --> 29:28.380
Had you had
the surgery --

29:28.380 --> 29:30.500
I wouldn't be raw hamburger
right now?

29:30.500 --> 29:32.080
[ Chuckles ]

29:33.880 --> 29:35.380
[ Clears throat ]

29:35.380 --> 29:37.460
Okay. So you're mad
at her, hmm?

29:37.460 --> 29:39.620
[ Sighs ]
Okay, I'm sorry, I --

29:41.670 --> 29:44.330
I didn't mean for you --
That was unprofessional of me.

29:44.330 --> 29:45.330
I apologize.

29:45.330 --> 29:46.750
Okay. So...

29:46.750 --> 29:48.250
Spill.

29:48.250 --> 29:51.250
Come on.
Give me the goods.

29:51.250 --> 29:53.460
Tell me the dirt,
tell me the skinny.

29:53.460 --> 29:55.290
Dr. Kepner.

29:56.830 --> 29:59.120
You really think I can't tell
when someone's in pain, too?

30:00.670 --> 30:02.830
That's not --

30:02.830 --> 30:05.460
You don't have to worry
about that --

30:05.460 --> 30:07.710
So, what, I should worry
about my wife not getting here

30:07.710 --> 30:08.750
before I pass out?

30:08.750 --> 30:10.420
Or the fact that my skin

30:10.420 --> 30:12.460
is giving up being actual,
you know, skin?

30:12.460 --> 30:14.080
I can give you
morphine and --

30:14.080 --> 30:16.080
No, no, listen, listen,
the Talmud says

30:16.080 --> 30:18.420
if someone is sick
or in need

30:18.420 --> 30:21.290
and you can take away
1/60th of their pain,

30:21.290 --> 30:23.670
then that's goodness.
That's God.

30:23.670 --> 30:27.210
You can't take away
a 60th of something

30:27.210 --> 30:29.880
if you don't know
what it is.

30:29.880 --> 30:31.000
That's not your job.

30:31.000 --> 30:33.210
It is exactly my job,

30:33.210 --> 30:35.620
and I prefer to do it
till the bitter end.

30:35.620 --> 30:38.540
Come on. You're not gonna deny
a dying man's wish?

30:38.540 --> 30:40.500
You're not --

30:40.500 --> 30:42.080
Aren't I?

30:42.080 --> 30:46.210
Dr. Kepner, I've held enough
dying men's hands in my career.

30:46.210 --> 30:48.710
I know
it's mine this time.

30:48.710 --> 30:50.670
♪♪

30:50.670 --> 30:52.330
I am sorry, Eli.

30:52.330 --> 30:54.330
Don't be sorry.
You're doing your job.

30:54.330 --> 30:56.420
Just let me do mine.
-[ Chuckles ]

30:56.420 --> 30:58.620
I'm not --

30:58.620 --> 30:59.750
I -- [ Scoffs ]

30:59.750 --> 31:01.790
I'm fine.

31:01.790 --> 31:03.460
I don't --
I don't need anything.

31:03.460 --> 31:05.210
[ Chuckles ] What?

31:05.210 --> 31:07.040
You're a terrible liar.
I like that.

31:08.330 --> 31:10.120
[ Sighs ]

31:10.120 --> 31:11.790
All right, fine.

31:11.790 --> 31:13.460
What's that saying?

31:13.460 --> 31:16.170
"If -- If I'm not for myself,
who will be for me?"

31:16.170 --> 31:19.000
Mm-hmm.
Well, I am taking care
of myself, for once.

31:19.000 --> 31:20.380
That's all.

31:20.380 --> 31:21.750
Oh, and you realize that
that phrase

31:21.750 --> 31:23.460
is not an invitation
for narcissism, right?

31:23.460 --> 31:25.210
You're calling me
a narcissist?

31:25.210 --> 31:26.880
Sure you don't
want more pain meds?

31:26.880 --> 31:28.710
It'll knock you right out.
-I don't blame you.

31:28.710 --> 31:30.040
You know,
it's human nature.

31:30.040 --> 31:32.830
You face enough hardship,
then you can't help but think

31:32.830 --> 31:34.500
that you're being punished,

31:34.500 --> 31:36.580
that you did something
to deserve it.

31:36.580 --> 31:38.080
I did nothing
to deserve --

31:38.080 --> 31:40.620
[ Monitor beeping ]

31:43.330 --> 31:46.830
Okay. My whole life,
I followed His rules.

31:46.830 --> 31:49.500
I studied, I believed,

31:49.500 --> 31:51.120
I practiced
what I preached.

31:51.120 --> 31:54.210
I did every single thing
He asked of me.

31:54.210 --> 31:57.380
And that
guarantees you...what?

31:57.380 --> 31:59.460
Excuse me?

31:59.460 --> 32:01.380
Well, where -- where --
where is the guarantee?

32:01.380 --> 32:03.000
In the sequel?
'Cause, I have to admit,

32:03.000 --> 32:04.330
I'm not as up on that
as I used to be.

32:04.330 --> 32:05.710
If by the sequel,
you mean the New Testament,

32:05.710 --> 32:07.080
that's pretty funny.
-No, no, where --

32:07.080 --> 32:09.040
where is it written exactly
that if you do this or that,

32:09.040 --> 32:11.880
that everything in your life's
gonna be good, hmm?

32:11.880 --> 32:14.620
Nowhere, in any faith,
is there a guarantee.

32:14.620 --> 32:17.790
I'm not asking for everything
to be good all the time.

32:17.790 --> 32:19.580
But fair -- I think that I --
-Fair?

32:19.580 --> 32:21.120
Was it fair when Isaac
went blind

32:21.120 --> 32:22.880
and then his child
betrayed him?

32:22.880 --> 32:25.620
And where was the fairness
when Sara had to wait 99 years

32:25.620 --> 32:27.880
before she had a child,
and God said, "Sacrifice him"?

32:27.880 --> 32:29.750
And Moses couldn't even get
past the bouncer

32:29.750 --> 32:31.170
to the Promised Land.

32:31.170 --> 32:32.540
And like I said,
I'm not up on the sequel,

32:32.540 --> 32:34.920
but from what I hear,
Jesus got a raw deal.

32:34.920 --> 32:37.290
-Oh, I --
-Nobody in the Bible

32:37.290 --> 32:40.790
lived a life free of suffering
or injustice,

32:40.790 --> 32:42.460
or it wouldn't have
been a best seller.

32:42.460 --> 32:44.290
And if they lived
lives like that,

32:44.290 --> 32:47.080
why should ours be diff--
[Gasps] different?

32:47.080 --> 32:48.620
[ Coughing ]

32:48.620 --> 32:49.670
Here we go.

32:49.670 --> 32:52.880
[ Grunts ]

32:52.880 --> 32:57.500
Now, if people only believed
in God when things were good,

32:57.500 --> 33:00.040
I guarantee you,
after the Holocaust,

33:00.040 --> 33:01.710
not a single Jew
would be a believer.

33:01.710 --> 33:03.500
[ Sighs ] Okay.

33:03.500 --> 33:05.580
Well, see, now you mention
the Holocaust,

33:05.580 --> 33:07.250
and anything I say
after that makes me --

33:07.250 --> 33:08.380
A narcissist?

33:08.380 --> 33:10.580
[ Laughing ] I was gonna say
jackass, but...

33:10.580 --> 33:12.000
-[ Laughs, Coughs ]
-Okay, come on.

33:12.000 --> 33:13.620
Deep breath.
Please, deep breath.

33:13.620 --> 33:15.920
There you go.

33:15.920 --> 33:18.170
-Mm. Mm-hmm.
-Okay.

33:20.250 --> 33:24.540
Faith wouldn't
be real faith...

33:24.540 --> 33:26.830
if you only believe
when things are good.

33:26.830 --> 33:28.540
[ Monitor beeping ]

33:30.750 --> 33:33.880
Well, so, what?

33:33.880 --> 33:36.540
The world is just cruel
and random,

33:36.540 --> 33:38.620
and there's nothing
anyone can do about it?

33:38.620 --> 33:40.080
Look, I don't have
a lot of time here.

33:40.080 --> 33:41.500
Do you mind if I just skip
to the part

33:41.500 --> 33:43.040
where I pretend I don't know
what to tell you?

33:43.040 --> 33:44.210
I'm just
gonna tell you, okay?

33:44.210 --> 33:45.880
-Okay.
-You sound like a child.

33:45.880 --> 33:47.880
-What?
-Terrible things happen.

33:47.880 --> 33:51.540
Terrible, wonderful,
devastating things happen.

33:51.540 --> 33:53.330
Who the hell are you
to know why?

33:53.330 --> 33:56.460
Who are you to know
why some people live

33:56.460 --> 33:57.670
and some people die?

33:57.670 --> 33:59.210
Children die.

33:59.210 --> 34:01.170
Children who didn't do
anything wrong,

34:01.170 --> 34:03.120
children...who were broken

34:03.120 --> 34:05.330
before they had a chance
to be whole,

34:05.330 --> 34:07.250
who were climbing
in their own front windows.

34:07.250 --> 34:10.960
Right. And you don't get to know
why any more than --

34:10.960 --> 34:13.250
than I get to know why
I'm dying

34:13.250 --> 34:15.250
from taking
a pill that saves lives,

34:15.250 --> 34:18.790
that saves...
nearly everyone's life...

34:18.790 --> 34:20.580
but it's killing me.

34:22.380 --> 34:24.880
So you can either
believe in God and goodness,

34:24.880 --> 34:26.790
or you can believe
it's pointless, it's cruel,

34:26.790 --> 34:30.080
and it's random...

34:30.080 --> 34:32.670
whatever makes you
happier.

34:32.670 --> 34:35.250
Are you?

34:35.250 --> 34:37.040
Happy?

34:41.210 --> 34:42.750
[ Sniffles ]

34:42.750 --> 34:44.750
It's not narcissism.

34:44.750 --> 34:46.330
Then what is it?

34:46.330 --> 34:47.920
[ Crying ]

34:47.920 --> 34:49.210
Pain.

34:52.210 --> 34:55.920
Unimaginable pain.

34:55.920 --> 34:57.580
Yeah, I know the feeling.

35:05.210 --> 35:08.540
God's not indifferent
to our pain.

35:08.540 --> 35:11.330
[ Sobs ]

35:11.330 --> 35:12.790
Listen, tikkun olam.

35:12.790 --> 35:14.830
Tikkun olam means...

35:14.830 --> 35:16.500
[ Sighs ]

35:16.500 --> 35:19.500
...that the world
is full of brokenness...

35:19.500 --> 35:23.250
and it's our job to put it
back together again.

35:23.250 --> 35:25.880
It assumes...

35:25.880 --> 35:28.080
that the world...

35:31.040 --> 35:34.750
...is, uh, broken
and in need and in pain.

35:37.960 --> 35:41.000
And it's our job...

35:41.000 --> 35:44.000
to fix -- f-fix it.

35:44.000 --> 35:47.790
Eli, let me -- let me
give you some more morphine.

35:47.790 --> 35:50.710
I can -- I can take away
the pain.

35:50.710 --> 35:52.080
[ Blows ]

35:52.080 --> 35:54.290
1/60th of your pain.
I can do that.

35:54.290 --> 35:56.500
Please...let me.

35:56.500 --> 35:58.920
You already did.

35:58.920 --> 36:03.250
♪♪

36:03.250 --> 36:05.330
Oh, and listen -- tell --

36:05.330 --> 36:07.170
Will you tell Dr. Bailey
I forgive her?

36:07.170 --> 36:08.830
Okay?
You'll -- You'll tell.

36:08.830 --> 36:10.120
You'll tell her, right?

36:10.120 --> 36:12.540
Eli -- Eli, no.

36:12.540 --> 36:14.540
You have to hang on
just a little bit longer.

36:14.540 --> 36:16.420
Elyse is on her way.
She's on her way.

36:16.420 --> 36:17.960
Elyse?
Elyse is here?

36:17.960 --> 36:19.620
She'll be here
any minute.

36:19.620 --> 36:22.000
♪♪

36:22.000 --> 36:25.880
Elyse.

36:25.880 --> 36:27.250
I...I love you...

36:27.250 --> 36:28.540
Okay.

36:28.540 --> 36:29.790
Okay, Eli.

36:29.790 --> 36:31.290
Okay.

36:31.290 --> 36:33.830
Oh, Elyse.

36:33.830 --> 36:37.170
Eli, I'm here.

36:37.170 --> 36:39.420
I love you.

36:39.420 --> 36:40.830
I'm right here.

36:40.830 --> 36:43.120
I love -- I love...

36:43.120 --> 36:45.460
[ Monitor beeping ]

36:45.460 --> 36:47.710
[ Flatline ]

36:47.710 --> 36:49.620
[ Sobbing ]

36:51.460 --> 36:53.290
Oh.

36:53.290 --> 36:58.580
♪♪

36:58.580 --> 37:00.380
Oh.

37:01.830 --> 37:04.290
[ Crying ]

37:04.290 --> 37:10.500
♪♪

37:23.670 --> 37:25.330
What's the word,
Dr. Grey?

37:27.750 --> 37:30.620
You taking the front of the
canoe or you taking the back?

37:30.620 --> 37:33.080
You making room for me
in that hammock of yours?

37:33.080 --> 37:35.120
[ Chuckles ]

37:35.120 --> 37:37.210
Sorry, Nick.

37:37.210 --> 37:40.210
Plan B is --
is never gonna happen.

37:40.210 --> 37:42.580
[ Sighs ]

37:44.120 --> 37:45.750
Because
I saved your kidney.

37:45.750 --> 37:47.960
Pbht! You are...

37:47.960 --> 37:49.460
Oh, my God.
You are evil.

37:49.460 --> 37:51.210
[ Both laugh ]

37:51.210 --> 37:52.580
An evil, twisted --

37:52.580 --> 37:53.710
Genius.

37:53.710 --> 37:55.500
Genius.

37:55.500 --> 37:56.750
You are.

37:56.750 --> 37:58.460
You saved my life.

37:58.460 --> 37:59.960
I did.

37:59.960 --> 38:03.120
[ Sighs ]
Saved my whole damn life.

38:03.120 --> 38:08.540
♪♪

38:08.540 --> 38:11.880
Teddy -- Teddy, you're blowing
this way out of proportion!

38:11.880 --> 38:13.580
I came here
because I love you!

38:13.580 --> 38:15.250
You came here because
your marriage is over,

38:15.250 --> 38:16.960
and you're terrified
of being alone!

38:16.960 --> 38:18.330
-I'm not terrified --
-Oh, please!

38:18.330 --> 38:20.170
You leave Beth for Cristina,

38:20.170 --> 38:23.080
and then Cristina
for some random woman in a bar,

38:23.080 --> 38:24.790
and then you go back
to Cristina,

38:24.790 --> 38:27.380
and then you go to Amelia
to soothe your pathological need

38:27.380 --> 38:29.120
to be coupled up
so that no one sees

38:29.120 --> 38:30.290
how sad
and empty you are!

38:30.290 --> 38:31.920
You're the one
who's scared.

38:31.920 --> 38:33.880
-I'm not scared!
-You always have been.

38:33.880 --> 38:36.330
Deep down, you're terrified
to be -- be happy.

38:36.330 --> 38:38.210
I mean, sure, you're fine
to marry the dead guy,

38:38.210 --> 38:39.500
but when you have love --
real love --

38:39.500 --> 38:40.880
staring you in the face,
you run!

38:40.880 --> 38:42.750
You don't ever get
to talk about Henry.

38:42.750 --> 38:44.960
Do you understand me?

38:44.960 --> 38:47.290
I am not scared.

38:47.290 --> 38:49.750
Please, it's what you do.
It's what you've always done.

38:49.750 --> 38:52.540
It's the reason you can't make
a real relationship work.

38:52.540 --> 38:55.290
You'd rather burn it all to
the ground than risk being hurt!

38:55.290 --> 38:57.210
Maybe because all you ever do
is hurt me, Owen!

38:57.210 --> 39:00.290
You string me along
for years

39:00.290 --> 39:01.960
with these half-baked
declarations,

39:01.960 --> 39:03.500
and then you marry
other women.

39:03.500 --> 39:05.880
And then you fly halfway across
the world to my doorstep,

39:05.880 --> 39:07.880
and you convince me
that this is real,

39:07.880 --> 39:09.500
that you're in this
with me,

39:09.500 --> 39:11.380
that you love me,
that you want me!

39:11.380 --> 39:14.670
And it has never, ever,
ever been about me!

39:14.670 --> 39:16.330
I do love you!

39:16.330 --> 39:17.920
I want you.

39:17.920 --> 39:20.170
And then, when you have me,
when you really have me,

39:20.170 --> 39:22.170
and you have me believing
that you mean it,

39:22.170 --> 39:24.120
I find out that 24 hours
earlier,

39:24.120 --> 39:27.120
your ex-wife, who you just
screwed, told you to!

39:27.120 --> 39:29.540
I am done
being your fallback.

39:29.540 --> 39:32.120
I am done
being your damn sloppy seconds.

39:32.120 --> 39:34.250
I'm not
your consolation prize!

39:34.250 --> 39:36.580
Teddy, please.
Please, Teddy,

39:36.580 --> 39:39.710
just look at me -- look at me.
Please.

39:39.710 --> 39:41.290
Don't do this.

39:47.000 --> 39:49.500
You know, the snow?

39:49.500 --> 39:52.460
It wasn't for the soldiers.
It was for you.

39:52.460 --> 39:54.120
I did it for you.

39:54.120 --> 39:56.170
I just knew
you loved Christmas,

39:56.170 --> 39:58.460
and I, uh --
I just wanted, uh...

40:00.790 --> 40:02.460
I did it for you.

40:06.080 --> 40:08.080
I'm done, Owen.
We're done.

40:10.420 --> 40:12.210
♪♪

40:12.210 --> 40:13.920
Owen: 24 hours.

40:13.920 --> 40:16.580
1,440 minutes.

40:16.580 --> 40:19.250
86,400 seconds.

40:19.250 --> 40:21.420
That's all it takes.

40:21.420 --> 40:25.670
To save your life,
change your life.

40:25.670 --> 40:28.250
♪ Every day is like the last ♪

40:28.250 --> 40:32.710
[ Crying ]

40:32.710 --> 40:36.580
♪ Future looks like the past ♪

40:36.580 --> 40:39.710
♪♪

40:39.710 --> 40:43.670
It's time to break
beyond this haze

40:43.670 --> 40:48.290
To my eyes,
to brighter days

40:48.290 --> 40:54.960
♪♪

40:54.960 --> 40:58.960
♪ A better way comes into view ♪

40:58.960 --> 41:01.830
[ Match scratches ]

41:01.830 --> 41:06.000
♪ There must be more
that I can chase away ♪

41:06.000 --> 41:11.500
♪ To find myself
in brighter days ♪

41:11.500 --> 41:17.620
♪♪

41:17.620 --> 41:23.420
♪ And I know I'll find
where I stand ♪

41:23.420 --> 41:30.330
♪ And I know
I'll find who I am ♪

41:30.330 --> 41:33.960
♪ Just who I am ♪

41:33.960 --> 41:36.170
Eli forgave you.

41:36.170 --> 41:39.420
♪ Somewhere just beyond myself ♪

41:39.420 --> 41:43.210
Some things just...happen,

41:43.210 --> 41:46.460
and we don't get
to know why.

41:46.460 --> 41:49.880
♪♪

41:49.880 --> 41:53.830
♪ It's more than
just a change of pace ♪

41:53.830 --> 41:56.080
♪ I find myself inside ♪

41:56.080 --> 42:00.290
April:
One single day can pull us
from the depths of despair.

42:00.290 --> 42:02.670
[ Door bell jingles ]

42:02.670 --> 42:05.250
♪♪

42:05.250 --> 42:08.170
♪ And I know
I'll find where I am ♪

42:08.170 --> 42:09.710
-Hey.
-Oh!

42:09.710 --> 42:10.750
You look like crap.

42:10.750 --> 42:12.290
I do not.

42:12.290 --> 42:13.460
Long day?

42:13.460 --> 42:16.210
I saved a transplant surgeon
today.

42:16.210 --> 42:17.250
Mm.

42:19.170 --> 42:23.380
He was smart and funny.

42:23.380 --> 42:24.460
And?

42:24.460 --> 42:25.500
Hot.

42:25.500 --> 42:27.000
And, so, what?
He's married?

42:27.000 --> 42:28.170
Nope.

42:28.170 --> 42:30.380
Gay?
Lives in a foreign country?

42:30.380 --> 42:31.830
Minnesota.

42:31.830 --> 42:33.170
Same difference.

42:33.170 --> 42:34.580
-[ Laughs ]
-So what's the problem?

42:36.330 --> 42:38.920
No problem.
He was just my patient.

42:38.920 --> 42:41.250
So he's smart, funny,
and hot, and --

42:41.250 --> 42:43.460
My patient.

42:43.460 --> 42:46.710
I really like
the way my life is now.

42:46.710 --> 42:48.920
I just...

42:48.920 --> 42:52.330
He made me feel something that
I haven't felt since Derek.

42:52.330 --> 42:55.670
But...you're his doctor.

42:55.670 --> 42:58.330
♪♪

42:58.330 --> 43:01.000
Is it really the worst thing
in the world,

43:01.000 --> 43:03.790
knowing it's out there
if you want it?

43:03.790 --> 43:07.750
No, it's not
the worst thing.

43:07.750 --> 43:09.380
Meredith:
And one single day

43:09.380 --> 43:12.000
can fill us
with more possibilities

43:12.000 --> 43:14.120
than we could imagine.

43:14.120 --> 43:19.500
♪♪

